U.S. War on Chinese Tech
From New York — — the worst diplomatic policy decision made by the previous generation (and even earlier generations) of Americans is the launch of the "war of choice" against Iraq in 2003, which claimed its purpose was to eliminate — — in reality, non-existent — — massive weapons of mass destruction.
The necessity of understanding the disastrous decision-making process behind this catastrophic decision has become unprecedentedly significant, since the same logic is being used today to justify similar U.S. misguided policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then U.S. Vice President Richard Cheney, who claimed that even if the risk of massive weapons falling into the hands of terrorists was small (e.g., 1%) we should take action as if this situation would inevitably occur.
However, this type of reasoning often leads to incorrect decisions.
However, the US and some of its allies are currently using Cheneyism to attack Chinese technology.
According to the US government, since we cannot be certain that Chinese technology is safe, we should deal with it as if it is definitely harmful and ban it.
A correct decision would apply probability estimates to each of the alternative measures.
Before one generation ago, US policymakers should have considered not only the (claimed) 1% risk of WMDs falling into the hands of terrorists but also the 99% risk of launching a war on the basis of multiple flawed premises.
By simply emphasizing that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) has diverted public attention and caused people to ignore that the Iraq War lacks legitimacy and would severely destabilize the Middle East and global politics.
But the issue with Cheneyism is not just that it acts on minuscule risks without considering the extremely high potential costs, but politicians will always incite fear for some unspoken purposes.
This is what American leaders are doing again: by pointing out and exaggerating some minuscule risks to instill panic about Chinese tech companies.
The most relevant (but not the only) case is the US government's attack on Huawei, a communication tech company.
The US is gradually closing the domestic market for the company and striving to kill its global business.
Like Iraq, the US may ultimately cause a pointless geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have constantly been following Huawei's technological advancements, because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can greatly promote the realization of eliminating poverty and other United Nations' sustainable development goals.
I also have similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and encourage the industry to improve their actions towards sustainable development goals.
I once wrote a brief preface for a report on this topic by Huawei (without payment) and was criticized by anti-China people for it, therefore I asked the industry's top leaders and government officials if there is any evidence to prove that Huawei has any out-of-line behavior, and I repeatedly got the answer that Huawei's behavior is no different from other reliable industry leaders.
However, the US government still believes that Huawei's 5G devices may harm global security.
US officials claim that the "backdoors" preserved in Huawei's software or hardware may allow the Chinese government to monitor globally.
They point out that China's laws require Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the fact is here now.
Huawei's 5G equipment is low-priced and of high quality, currently leading many competitors and has already started to be promoted.
Its high performance stems from massive investments in research and development over the years, economies of scale, and experience in China's digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology to its sustainable development, it would be foolish for low-income economies around the world to refuse to launch 5G early.
However, despite being unable to produce any evidence of backdoors existing, the US is still lobbying the world to stay away from Huawei.
US claims are universal.
As a US Federal Communications Commissioner said: "Countries with 5G will have relevant innovation and set standards for other parts of the world, and this country is unlikely to be the US at present."
Other countries - especially the UK - have not yet found any backdoors in Huawei's hardware and software.
Even if backdoors are found in the future, it's almost certain that they can be closed by then.
Discussion about Huawei is also heated in Germany, as the US government threatened to reduce intelligence cooperation unless the authorities blocked Huawei's 5G technology.
Perhaps under the pressure of the US, the head of the German Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement similar to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not a field suitable for a group that cannot be fully trusted to participate in."
However, he was unable to provide any concrete evidence of wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel is fighting behind the scenes to open up the market to Huawei.
But ironically, the US complaints actually reflect some of the US's own surveillance activities at home and abroad — although this is no longer news.
China's equipment may make it harder for the US government to implement secret surveillance.
However, any government's unjust surveillance actions should be stopped.
The UN's independent supervision to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional safeguards over a technological war.
The threatening impact of the US's demand to ban Huawei is not limited to the early rollout of 5G networks, but has also posed a huge risk to the rule-based trading system.
Nowadays, the US is no longer a global leader in technology without dispute, and US President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete based on rules.
Their goal is to curb China's technological rise.
At the same time, they are also trying to eliminate the World Trade Organization by paralyzing its dispute resolution mechanism, which also reflects their pattern of undermining global rules.
If the Trump government can "successfully" divide the world into different technology camps, the risk of future conflicts will increase exponentially.
After World War II, the US advocated for open trade, which not only increased global efficiency, expanded the US technology market, but also reversed the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
While the collapse of a part of the reason is the United States imposed under the 1930 Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act protectionist tariffs, this tariff exacerbated the Great Depression, which in turn promoted the rise of Hitler and ultimately pushed the outbreak of World War II.
Just as in other fields, in the international arena, stimulating fear and taking action based on fear —— rather than following the evidence —— is a path leading to destruction.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules, which is the safest approach.
Let us establish independent monitoring institutions to reduce the threat of any country using the global network to monitor or launch a cyber war on other countries.
In this way, the world can quickly use breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
